===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|fro}} {{term|alegier|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|alleviare|alleviāre|lang=la}}, present active infinitive of {{term|allevio|alleviō|lighten|lang=la}}, from {{term|ad|lang=la}} + {{term|levis||light|lang=la}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|alleg|ing}}

# {{obsolete}} To [[lighten]], [[diminish]].
#* '''1485''', Sir Thomas Malory, ''Le Morte Darthur'', Book V:
#*: and suffir never your soveraynté to be '''alledged''' with your subjects, nother the soveraygne of your persone and londys.
#* '''1590''', Edmund Spenser, ''The Faerie Queene'', III.ii:
#*: Hart that is inly hurt, is greatly eased / With hope of thing, that may '''allegge''' his smart [...].

===Etymology 2===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|aleggen|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|xno}} {{term|aleger|lang=fro}}, the form from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|esligier|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|ML.}} *{{term||exlītigāre|to clear at law}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|ex||out}} + {{term|litigo|lītigō|sue at law|lang=la}}, the meaning from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|alleguer|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|allegare|allēgāre|lang=la}}, present active infinitive of {{term|allego|allēgō|send, depute; relate, mention, adduce|lang=la}}, from {{term|ad||to|lang=la}} + {{term|lego|lēgō|send|lang=la}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|alleg|ing}}

# {{obsolete|transitive}} To [[state]] under [[oath]], to [[plead]].
# {{archaic}} To [[cite]] or [[quote]] an author or his work ''for'' or ''against''.
# {{transitive}} To [[adduce]] (something) as a reason, excuse, support etc.
#* '''1603''', John Florio, translating Michel de Montaigne, ''Essays'', I.39:
#*: I will further '''alleage''' a storie [...] to make us palpably feele his naturall condition.
# {{transitive}} To make a [[claim]] as [[justification]] or [[proof]]; to make an assertion without proof.
#: {{usex|The agency '''alleged''' my credit history had problems.}}

